1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,860
[ HEARTBEAT ]

2
00:00:02,860 --> 00:00:04,800
NINA: <i>Abstract image of an eye.</i>

3
00:00:05,770 --> 00:00:09,000
[ ♪ PERCUSSION AND SYNTH STARTS ♪ ]
Am I crazy? Am I blind?

4
00:00:09,240 --> 00:00:11,950
Should I be hard
or should I be kind

5
00:00:11,950 --> 00:00:14,140
as I stand and shake my head?

6
00:00:14,880 --> 00:00:17,190
For no one knows what I see,

7
00:00:17,190 --> 00:00:19,840
yet I am always there to please.

8
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:22,400
<i>Colours wash over the screen.</i>

9
00:00:23,020 --> 00:00:25,310
[ ♪ MUSIC RISES ♪ ]
MILES: They're not real,

10
00:00:25,310 --> 00:00:26,800
or they're more real,

11
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:30,220
should I say than,
maybe a sighted person can imagine.

12
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:33,300
You probably do without realising,

13
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:35,630
but you can feel when things are there,

14
00:00:35,630 --> 00:00:37,600
even if you're not touching them.

15
00:00:38,480 --> 00:00:41,520
You learn,
as someone who can't see at all,

16
00:00:41,520 --> 00:00:43,180
to rely on that feeling.

17
00:00:43,280 --> 00:00:45,760
It, you know,
it saves you.

18
00:00:46,700 --> 00:00:49,280
And these hallucinations are so,
so real,

19
00:00:49,580 --> 00:00:51,610
[ ♪ MUSIC CLIMAXES ♪ ]
yes, you can see them,

20
00:00:51,610 --> 00:00:53,740
but you also...
feel them.

21
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,740
[ ♪ MUSIC STOPS SUDDENLY AND FADES ♪ ]

22
00:01:01,420 --> 00:01:03,140
NARRATOR: Aspectum

23
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:05,560
MILES: <i>I'm Miles.</i>

24
00:01:05,560 --> 00:01:07,860

<i>I'm at the empty cricket stadium.</i>

25
00:01:07,860 --> 00:01:09,740
[ DISTANT SHOUTING ]
Started playing County

26
00:01:09,740 --> 00:01:11,790
and then started playing

27
00:01:11,790 --> 00:01:16,040
International England cricket
from '98 through 2008.

28
00:01:16,400 --> 00:01:19,080
[ BALL THUDDING ]
It's a lot of really good fun.

29
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:22,030
It was...
Got to see places around the world

30
00:01:22,030 --> 00:01:26,180
that I wouldn't have been able to see
had I been able to see.

31
00:01:27,260 --> 00:01:31,170
Through just playing cricket,
the sport that I've loved since I was

32
00:01:31,170 --> 00:01:33,120
[ LAWN MOVER ]
as far back as I can remember.

33
00:01:33,120 --> 00:01:36,540
My dad, when I was five years old,
sat on the sofa with him

34
00:01:36,540 --> 00:01:38,300
explaining fielding positions.

35
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:45,660
When I was 18 months old,
my mom noticed that the pupil in my right eye

36
00:01:45,660 --> 00:01:49,400
wasn't working properly
when she turned the lights on and off,

37
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,230
and took me off down to the doctors.

38
00:01:51,230 --> 00:01:54,280
[ CRACKLING NOISE ]
Then went straight down there

39
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:58,160
and was diagnosed with Retina Blastoma,
so it's a cancer of the retina.

40
00:01:58,490 --> 00:02:01,030
[ NOISE BUILDING ]
It was in both eyes,

41
00:02:01,030 --> 00:02:02,650
but it was much further progressed

42
00:02:02,650 --> 00:02:04,840
in my right eye.

43
00:02:05,300 --> 00:02:08,260
So far so
they had to remove that eye instantly,

44
00:02:08,260 --> 00:02:09,100
and straight away.

45
00:02:09,220 --> 00:02:13,970
They reckoned that five weeks later,
the cancer would have been into the optic nerve

46
00:02:13,970 --> 00:02:16,380
and the brain
and that would have been <i>it</i>.

47
00:02:16,380 --> 00:02:18,300
And that would be the end of stuff.

48
00:02:18,300 --> 00:02:21,160
[ STADIUM AMBIENCE AND SINE WAVE ]

49
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:27,340
I did radiotherapy on my left eye
for the next three years.

50
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:31,920
Cobalt plaques on the back of the eyeball
and all that sort of stuff

51
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:34,800
to try and fry the cancer.

52
00:02:36,240 --> 00:02:38,230
But in the end,
it didn't work.

53
00:02:38,230 --> 00:02:39,600
It was too resilient.

54
00:02:40,820 --> 00:02:44,040
So they took my left eye
when I was four and a half.

55
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:45,980
[ CRACKLING NOISE STARTS ]

56
00:02:45,980 --> 00:02:47,330
NINA: <i>I'm Nina.</i>

57
00:02:47,330 --> 00:02:50,370
I developed a sight condition
when I was two years old.

58
00:02:50,370 --> 00:02:52,980
I caught the flu virus
and it attacked my eyes.

59
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:55,860
It left me with different problems.

60
00:02:56,860 --> 00:03:02,460
I lost my right eye 13 years ago
in an accident at work.

61
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:06,450
[ CLINKING ]
And then I lost the retina out of the left eye

62
00:03:06,450 --> 00:03:08,780
coming up to four years ago now

63
00:03:08,780 --> 00:03:10,500
in an accident at home.

64
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
[ DEEP DRONE ]

65
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,660
That morning I was taking too much on,

66
00:03:16,660 --> 00:03:19,100
[ KETTLE WHISTLING ]
doing the payroll for the staff at the cafe,

67
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:21,830
I was trying to get my son ready for school.

68
00:03:21,830 --> 00:03:25,480
I bent over,
basically caught the corner of the TV

69
00:03:25,480 --> 00:03:28,650
and it burst a hole in the top of my eyeball.

70
00:03:28,650 --> 00:03:31,640
And I knew straight away
the site just, it went just black.

71
00:03:32,180 --> 00:03:34,940
There was just like lines of lightning.

72
00:03:34,940 --> 00:03:38,700
[ DRONE SWELLING ]
And I just knew. I knew that the site had gone.

73
00:03:39,580 --> 00:03:40,980
It was quite frightening.

74
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:47,680
I came around from surgery
and I just saw waves of blue and red

75
00:03:49,100 --> 00:03:50,110
and I thought,

76
00:03:50,110 --> 00:03:52,080
"They've saved something that I can see,

77
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:54,640
"I can see something
they've saved some of my sight."

78
00:03:55,100 --> 00:03:58,280
Doctor came back
and I remember these words,

79
00:03:58,700 --> 00:04:01,840
he said: "I can reassure you
we haven't saved your sight,

80
00:04:01,840 --> 00:04:04,450
"it's just your mind playing tricks on you."

81
00:04:04,450 --> 00:04:08,640
So those words kind of haunted me
because I thought,

82
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:11,980
"Well, I can see something,
there's something there for sure."

83
00:04:11,980 --> 00:04:13,240
[ SINE WAVES FADE IN ]

84
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:17,120
Because he said that to me
I was really scared to tell anybody.

85
00:04:18,020 --> 00:04:22,020
[ FLOWING WATER ]
<i>Waves of blue, yellow, and green wash over the screen.</i>

86
00:04:22,020 --> 00:04:24,990
The images started to develop from that point,

87
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:29,340
and I started seeing patterns
and shapes and the colours,

88
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:34,580
the blue and red turned into
green and yellow and pink,

89
00:04:34,580 --> 00:04:37,530
and purple,
and then they started forming shapes,

90
00:04:37,530 --> 00:04:42,020
and then they became faces
and the faces were

91
00:04:42,640 --> 00:04:46,700
kind of turned into like a skull,
a zombie skull

92
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:48,560
and they had no eyes in the sockets

93
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:50,360
and they had blood dripping down the cheeks.

94
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:53,020
[ DISSONANT SOUNDS ]
It just become too scary.

95
00:04:53,020 --> 00:04:57,540
I was just sat there crying,
kind of huddled on the sofa in the corner

96
00:04:57,540 --> 00:04:59,780
just scared of these zombies that were there.

97
00:05:00,180 --> 00:05:02,740
<i>Here's some artwork I made of the skulls.</i>

98
00:05:02,740 --> 00:05:06,640
MILES: <i>We enter a doll's house recreation
of my childhood home.</i>

99
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:09,120
[ ♪ EERIE PIANO
AND REVERSED SOUNDS STARTS ♪ ]

100
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:14,700
So I first started getting hallucinations
when I was probably about four.

101
00:05:15,160 --> 00:05:19,160
I think it was just before
I totally lost my sight.

102
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,020
Mine have always been
what I've always called "monsters".

103
00:05:23,660 --> 00:05:26,740
Ones that were good,
ones that were friendly,

104
00:05:26,740 --> 00:05:28,440
[ STAIRS CREAK ]
ones that weren't.

105
00:05:28,440 --> 00:05:31,640
So I guess the friendly ones,
they just sort of sat back.

106
00:05:31,660 --> 00:05:33,660
They were never a threat.
[ WHOOSHES ]

107
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:37,760
There were two in particular I remember
when I was young,

108
00:05:37,760 --> 00:05:39,660
and they were sort of snakes,

109
00:05:39,660 --> 00:05:41,780
[ HISSES ]
and they were not friendly.

110
00:05:41,780 --> 00:05:52,740
They... were as thick as your arm,
and they had kind of thick, wormy hair.

111
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:55,500
When you're a child,
and your parents have gone out,

112
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:57,760
and your grandparents
are sitting for the evening,

113
00:05:57,760 --> 00:06:00,000
and you've gone to bed,
sometimes, you know, as a child,

114
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,270
you'd wake up and go:
"Oh, I want me mum, I want me dad!"

115
00:06:02,270 --> 00:06:03,200
or whatever.

116
00:06:03,200 --> 00:06:09,400
I couldn't go to the door to call downstairs
to my gran or my granddad or whatever

117
00:06:09,400 --> 00:06:11,200
because as soon as I opened the door a crack...

118
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:12,780
[ STEPS CREAK ]

119
00:06:12,780 --> 00:06:14,960
[ DRUMS START ]
one or both of these snakes would be outside

120
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:18,520
and they'd try and come through the door.

121
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:23,000
So you might whip it open, shout, slam it,
and dive back into bed again...

122
00:06:23,570 --> 00:06:25,440
but you probably wouldn't.

123
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:29,480
So you either just shouted a lot from there
or you bottled everything up

124
00:06:29,870 --> 00:06:32,660
and got under the duvet
where you couldn't see,

125
00:06:32,660 --> 00:06:33,840
metaphorically speaking.

126
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:35,420
Because that works for me.

127
00:06:36,030 --> 00:06:39,850
If I'm seeing a monster,
if I cover my eyes, I can't see it.

128
00:06:40,380 --> 00:06:41,440
Work that one out.

129
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:47,900
NINA: <i>I walk through a mirror maze with my cane,
reflections of myself appearing and disappearing.</i>

130
00:06:48,160 --> 00:06:51,280
It does have an impact
and I know some days I feel like,

131
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:54,020
[ PERCUSSIONS ]
"God, I just can't carry on. I'm just this...

132
00:06:54,020 --> 00:06:55,380
I can't cope with this anymore,

133
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:57,760
I need to shut, I need to close,
I need to go away,

134
00:06:57,760 --> 00:07:01,380
I need to get away, I need to escape it
and I can't escape it,

135
00:07:01,380 --> 00:07:03,850
it's there and I have
them bad days.

136
00:07:04,020 --> 00:07:08,550
So for me,
I experience them all day, every day.

137
00:07:08,970 --> 00:07:12,600
So from the moment I waked,
to the moment I get to sleep

138
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:16,770
or when I get to sleep
because that is one thing that I struggle with,

139
00:07:17,870 --> 00:07:22,170
getting to sleep
because when the hallucinations are there,

140
00:07:22,170 --> 00:07:25,400
they're there when I close my eyes,
they don't go away.

141
00:07:26,020 --> 00:07:29,340
It drives me insane sometimes(!)

142
00:07:29,340 --> 00:07:34,440
I just, like... I know it sounds,
and I probably shouldn't say this in front of everyone

143
00:07:34,440 --> 00:07:39,610
but it sounds like some days,
and especially it's more at nighttime

144
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:41,370
when I'm trying to get to sleep, but...

145
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:47,130
I smack myself on the head.
I shake.

146
00:07:48,160 --> 00:07:52,110
You know, I lie there in bed crying,
begging for it to go away

147
00:07:52,110 --> 00:07:54,020
because I just want to go to sleep.

148
00:07:54,980 --> 00:07:56,920
And that is really difficult to live with.

149
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:02,660
And when you can't make it go away,
that's hard.

150
00:08:04,910 --> 00:08:07,850
And then you know, and then you feel,
then you get guilt and shame

151
00:08:07,850 --> 00:08:11,350
for whacking yourself on the head
to try and make it go away.

152
00:08:12,110 --> 00:08:14,020
Because it can be so lonely.

153
00:08:14,520 --> 00:08:16,940
You know,
nobody knows what I'm going through,

154
00:08:16,940 --> 00:08:18,560
no one can see what I see.

155
00:08:18,950 --> 00:08:21,600
I'm trying to explain it to people.

156
00:08:22,250 --> 00:08:24,470
You don't know if they're going to think
you're crazy,

157
00:08:24,470 --> 00:08:27,100
or they're gonna empathise,
or they're gonna...

158
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:29,190
You just don't know how they're going to react.

159
00:08:30,880 --> 00:08:35,080
MILES: <i>I'm sitting in the garden with NUSHKA,</i>
<i>my German Shepherd guide dog.</i>

160
00:08:35,080 --> 00:08:37,360
[ BIRDS CHIRPING; DOG WHINING ]
How do you tell someone?

161
00:08:37,530 --> 00:08:39,220
I don't know, I really don't know.

162
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:43,520
It was just something that I lived with,
it was just there. I told a friend of mine  

163
00:08:43,520 --> 00:08:48,880
about them probably when I was about
seven, six, seven, something like that.

164
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:53,010
Not “Oh, I see these monsters”,
it was just: “There are these monsters”.

165
00:08:53,040 --> 00:08:56,830
And I suspect at that age he probably

166
00:08:56,840 --> 00:08:59,110
[ BIRDS CHIRPING ]
took it as a game.

167
00:08:59,240 --> 00:09:04,760
But also I think he probably
knew to a point there was something.

168
00:09:04,960 --> 00:09:07,040
Because he would ask, he'd say

169
00:09:07,040 --> 00:09:11,610
"What monsters are there today?
Which ones are they? Let's get them!"

170
00:09:11,860 --> 00:09:14,290
[ BIRDS CHIRPING; DOG WHINING ]
And we'd charge down the corridor,

171
00:09:14,380 --> 00:09:18,330
we’d-we’d attack these things,
a-and it actually felt quite good,

172
00:09:18,410 --> 00:09:21,100
just to actually be on the front foot,
felt…

173
00:09:21,150 --> 00:09:23,390
[ EXHALES ]
felt good.

174
00:09:23,390 --> 00:09:24,620
[ DOG WHINING ]

175
00:09:26,520 --> 00:09:29,720
[ WATER FLOWING ]
NINA: <i>Reflections of images through water.</i>

176
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:33,520
[ ♪ MELANCHOLIC SYNTHS ♪ ]
From the moment I was told

177
00:09:33,530 --> 00:09:36,570
that it was just my mind,
and I saw those wavy colours,

178
00:09:37,130 --> 00:09:40,980
it was probably about five
or six weeks that I kept it to myself,

179
00:09:40,990 --> 00:09:46,720
which is, doesn't seem 
that long but for me, it felt like months

180
00:09:46,720 --> 00:09:50,630
and it got to the point where I just,
like, I can't do this alone anymore.

181
00:09:50,640 --> 00:09:52,900
I have to speak to somebody

182
00:09:52,920 --> 00:09:56,090
but I was really scared of telling anyone,
because I thought,

183
00:09:56,110 --> 00:09:58,940
“They're going to think I'm going mad."

184
00:09:58,960 --> 00:10:01,400
"What you mean you can see someone
in the corner of the room?

185
00:10:01,400 --> 00:10:04,260
"What do you mean you can see a crocodile
crawling across the living room?

186
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:06,480
“Are you going crazy? You're mental?”

187
00:10:06,480 --> 00:10:09,580
They're gonna think
that I'm having a nervous breakdown,

188
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:12,490
because I've lost my sight,
and I've lost my business

189
00:10:12,520 --> 00:10:15,110
and I've lost, you know…

190
00:10:15,130 --> 00:10:18,830
stick me on a load of tablets,
and I'm just going to become a vegetable in the  

191
00:10:18,840 --> 00:10:25,000
corner of the room. So, I was really scared
to tell anyone. So I told my mom and husband

192
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:30,600
and they didn't have a clue, but they were
really understanding and patient and  

193
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:33,500
"Right let's try
and find out what's going on."

194
00:10:33,540 --> 00:10:36,920
And that's when I came across
Judith Potts and Esme's Umbrella.

195
00:10:36,920 --> 00:10:38,920
[ BIRDS CHIRPING ]
So, I emailed her

196
00:10:38,950 --> 00:10:41,160
and explained what I was going through

197
00:10:41,190 --> 00:10:43,970
and she replied and said

198
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:48,520
"Yeah, you've got Charles Bonnet syndrome."
And I was like "Wooh, what's that?"

199
00:10:48,520 --> 00:10:52,310
It just felt amazing that
she's told me that I have this condition.

200
00:10:52,460 --> 00:10:56,900
It's got a name. Wow!
Even though I had no idea what it was,

201
00:10:57,180 --> 00:11:03,880
I had something that had a name,
and a partial explanation.

202
00:11:03,880 --> 00:11:05,520
[ ♪ ORCHESTRAL MUSIC ♪ ]
MILES: <i>Back in the doll's house,</i>

203
00:11:05,570 --> 00:11:07,000
<i>a documentary is playing on TV.</i>

204
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,000
<i>We hear from Judith Potts, Prof</i>
<i>Mariya Moosajee, and Prof Dominic Ffytche.</i>

205
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,330
JUDITH: When you full sight, there
are messages which run all the time

206
00:11:16,330 --> 00:11:20,350
from the retina in the eye
to the visual cortex in the brain.

207
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:26,440
The eye acting like a camera and the brain
interpreting what it is you're seeing.

208
00:11:26,440 --> 00:11:30,080
When sight diminishes,
those messages slow down

209
00:11:30,080 --> 00:11:34,240
or stop entirely.
But the brain doesn't.

210
00:11:34,340 --> 00:11:39,840
The brain doesn't kind of retire at that
point, the brain, with nothing to interpret 

211
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:46,320
fires up, and creates its own images,
which are the visual hallucinations.

212
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,550
MARIYA: These are
purely visual hallucinations.

213
00:11:49,570 --> 00:11:52,710
and they're not linked
to any kind of mental illness.

214
00:11:52,830 --> 00:11:55,750
Charles Bonnet syndrome is a side effect

215
00:11:55,810 --> 00:12:02,520
of losing one's vision, and
it manifests as visual hallucinations.

216
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:06,840
If you could imagine,
if you're looking at your surroundings

217
00:12:06,840 --> 00:12:11,980
and part of your eye isn't working
properly, and it can't see very well,

218
00:12:12,020 --> 00:12:16,560
it could be like a jigsaw. There are
parts of the jigsaw with the pieces there

219
00:12:16,560 --> 00:12:19,560
and then there are dark bits,
where the pieces aren't present.  

220
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:22,080
Your brain realises
that there are gaps in  

221
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:27,600
your vision, and it tries to fill
those gaps with an image.

222
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:30,440
DOMINIC:
So Charles Bonnet syndrome ranges from

223
00:12:30,440 --> 00:12:33,480
very simple types of hallucination.

224
00:12:33,570 --> 00:12:37,370
It could be just a colour blob
or a line, to about 60% of people

225
00:12:37,370 --> 00:12:40,170
